# Likelihood fundamentals demonstration
demonstrate_likelihood_fundamentals <- function() {
  
  cat("=== LIKELIHOOD FUNDAMENTALS DEMONSTRASIYASI ===\n")
  
  # Simple example: 1 person, 1 item
  cat("Simple Example: 1 person, 1 item, 2PL model\n\n")
  
  # Item parameters
  discrimination <- 1.5
  difficulty <- 0.5
  
  # Person ability range
  theta_range <- seq(-3, 3, by = 0.1)
  
  # Observed response
  observed_response <- 1  # Person got item correct
  
  # Calculate likelihood for each theta value
  likelihoods <- numeric(length(theta_range))
  
  for(i in 1:length(theta_range)) {
    theta_i <- theta_range[i]
    
    # 2PL probability
    prob <- exp(discrimination * (theta_i - difficulty)) / 
            (1 + exp(discrimination * (theta_i - difficulty)))
    
    # Likelihood given observed response
    if(observed_response == 1) {
      likelihoods[i] <- prob
    } else {
      likelihoods[i] <- 1 - prob
    }
  }
  
  # Find maximum likelihood estimate
  mle_index <- which.max(likelihoods)
  mle_theta <- theta_range[mle_index]
  
  # Plot likelihood function
  plot(theta_range, likelihoods, type = "l", lwd = 3, col = "blue",
       main = "Likelihood Function: 1 Person, 1 Item",
       xlab = "Theta (Person Ability)", ylab = "Likelihood",
       ylim = c(0, max(likelihoods) * 1.1))
  
  # Mark MLE
  abline(v = mle_theta, lty = 2, col = "red", lwd = 2)
  points(mle_theta, max(likelihoods), col = "red", pch = 19, cex = 1.5)
  
  text(mle_theta + 0.5, max(likelihoods) * 0.9, 
       paste("MLE =", round(mle_theta, 2)), col = "red")
  
  grid(TRUE)
  
  cat("Single Item MLE Results:\n")
  cat("Item difficulty:", difficulty, "\n")
  cat("Item discrimination:", discrimination, "\n")
  cat("Observed response:", observed_response, "\n")
  cat("MLE of theta:", round(mle_theta, 3), "\n")
  cat("Maximum likelihood:", round(max(likelihoods), 3), "\n\n")
  
  return(list(
    theta_range = theta_range,
    likelihoods = likelihoods,
    mle_theta = mle_theta
  ))
}

# Demonstrate likelihood with multiple items
demonstrate_multiple_items_likelihood <- function() {
  
  cat("Multiple Items Likelihood: 1 person, 5 items\n\n")
  
  # Item parameters
  discriminations <- c(1.2, 1.8, 1.0, 2.0, 1.5)
  difficulties <- c(-1.0, -0.5, 0.0, 0.5, 1.0)
  
  # Observed response pattern
  observed_pattern <- c(1, 1, 1, 0, 0)  # Consistent with moderate ability
  
  # Person ability range
  theta_range <- seq(-3, 3, by = 0.1)
  
  # Calculate likelihood for each theta
  likelihoods <- numeric(length(theta_range))
  log_likelihoods <- numeric(length(theta_range))
  
  for(t in 1:length(theta_range)) {
    theta_t <- theta_range[t]
    
    # Calculate likelihood across all items
    person_likelihood <- 1
    person_log_likelihood <- 0
    
    for(j in 1:length(discriminations)) {
      # 2PL probability
      prob <- exp(discriminations[j] * (theta_t - difficulties[j])) / 
              (1 + exp(discriminations[j] * (theta_t - difficulties[j])))
      
      # Likelihood contribution
      if(observed_pattern[j] == 1) {
        person_likelihood <- person_likelihood * prob
        person_log_likelihood <- person_log_likelihood + log(prob)
      } else {
        person_likelihood <- person_likelihood * (1 - prob)
        person_log_likelihood <- person_log_likelihood + log(1 - prob)
      }
    }
    
    likelihoods[t] <- person_likelihood
    log_likelihoods[t] <- person_log_likelihood
  }
  
  # Find MLE
  mle_index <- which.max(likelihoods)
  mle_theta <- theta_range[mle_index]
  
  # Create plots
  par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
  
  # Likelihood plot
  plot(theta_range, likelihoods, type = "l", lwd = 3, col = "blue",
       main = "Likelihood Function (5 Items)",
       xlab = "Theta", ylab = "Likelihood")
  abline(v = mle_theta, lty = 2, col = "red", lwd = 2)
  grid(TRUE)
  
  # Log-likelihood plot
  plot(theta_range, log_likelihoods, type = "l", lwd = 3, col = "green",
       main = "Log-Likelihood Function (5 Items)",
       xlab = "Theta", ylab = "Log-Likelihood")
  abline(v = mle_theta, lty = 2, col = "red", lwd = 2)
  grid(TRUE)
  
  par(mfrow = c(1, 1))
  
  cat("Multiple Items Results:\n")
  cat("Response pattern:", paste(observed_pattern, collapse = ", "), "\n")
  cat("MLE of theta:", round(mle_theta, 3), "\n")
  cat("Maximum likelihood:", format(max(likelihoods), scientific = TRUE), "\n")
  cat("Maximum log-likelihood:", round(max(log_likelihoods), 3), "\n\n")
  
  # Show individual item contributions
  item_contributions <- data.frame(
    Item = 1:5,
    Discrimination = discriminations,
    Difficulty = difficulties,
    Response = observed_pattern,
    Probability_at_MLE = numeric(5),
    Log_Lik_Contribution = numeric(5)
  )
  
  for(j in 1:5) {
    prob <- exp(discriminations[j] * (mle_theta - difficulties[j])) / 
            (1 + exp(discriminations[j] * (mle_theta - difficulties[j])))
    
    item_contributions$Probability_at_MLE[j] <- round(prob, 3)
    
    if(observed_pattern[j] == 1) {
      item_contributions$Log_Lik_Contribution[j] <- round(log(prob), 3)
    } else {
      item_contributions$Log_Lik_Contribution[j] <- round(log(1 - prob), 3)
    }
  }
  
  print(item_contributions)
  
  return(list(
    theta_range = theta_range,
    likelihoods = likelihoods,
    log_likelihoods = log_likelihoods,
    mle_theta = mle_theta,
    item_contributions = item_contributions
  ))
}

# JML demonstration
demonstrate_jml_approach <- function() {
  
  cat("=== JML APPROACH DEMONSTRASIYASI ===\n")
  
  # Generate small dataset for demonstration
  set.seed(54321)
  n_persons <- 20
  n_items <- 8
  
  sim_data <- simulate_irt_data_mle(n_persons, n_items, "2PL")
  
  cat("Dataset for JML:\n")
  cat("Persons:", n_persons, "\n")
  cat("Items:", n_items, "\n")
  cat("Total parameters:", n_persons + 2*n_items, "\n\n")
  
  # JML estimation (simplified implementation)
  cat("JML Estimation Process:\n")
  
  # Initial parameter values
  initial_theta <- qlogis((rowSums(sim_data$data) + 0.5) / (n_items + 1))
  initial_discriminations <- rep(1, n_items)
  initial_difficulties <- qlogis((colSums(sim_data$data) + 0.5) / (n_persons + 1))
  
  # Combine all parameters
  initial_params <- c(initial_discriminations, initial_difficulties, initial_theta)
  
  cat("Initial parameter summary:\n")
  cat("Discrimination range:", round(min(initial_discriminations), 3), "to", 
      round(max(initial_discriminations), 3), "\n")
  cat("Difficulty range:", round(min(initial_difficulties), 3), "to", 
      round(max(initial_difficulties), 3), "\n")
  cat("Theta range:", round(min(initial_theta), 3), "to", 
      round(max(initial_theta), 3), "\n\n")
  
  # Simple optimization attempt (would need more sophisticated in practice)
  tryCatch({
    
    # This is a simplified optimization - real JML more complex
    cat("JML optimization attempted...\n")
    
    # Calculate initial log-likelihood
    initial_loglik <- -log_likelihood_2pl(initial_params, sim_data$data)
    cat("Initial log-likelihood:", round(initial_loglik, 2), "\n")
    
    # Note: Full optimization would be computationally intensive
    cat("Note: Full JML optimization requires sophisticated algorithms\n\n")
    
  }, error = function(e) {
    cat("JML optimization encountered issues:", e$message, "\n")
  })
  
  # JML advantages and disadvantages
  cat("=== JML ADVANTAGES vs DISADVANTAGES ===\n")
  
  jml_comparison <- data.frame(
    Aspect = c("Conceptual Simplicity", "Parameter Estimates", "Computational Cost", 
               "Incidental Parameters", "Bias", "Convergence"),
    
    Advantage = c("Straightforward approach", "Direct estimates", "Single optimization", 
                  "All parameters estimated", "Unbiased (asymptotically)", "Clear objective"),
    
    Disadvantage = c("High-dimensional optimization", "Inconsistent estimates", "Very expensive", 
                     "Too many parameters", "Biased in finite samples", "Often fails"),
    
    Practical_Impact = c("Implementation difficulty", "Poor precision", "Slow analysis", 
                         "Overparameterization", "Unreliable results", "Analysis failure")
  )
  
  print(jml_comparison)
  
  return(list(
    data = sim_data$data,
    true_params = sim_data$true_params,
    initial_params = list(
      theta = initial_theta,
      discriminations = initial_discriminations,
      difficulties = initial_difficulties
    )
  ))
}

# Demonstrate JML bias (incidental parameters problem)
demonstrate_jml_bias <- function() {
  
  cat("JML Bias: The Incidental Parameters Problem\n\n")
  
  # Simulation study showing JML bias
  set.seed(67890)
  
  sample_sizes <- c(50, 100, 200, 500, 1000)
  n_items <- 10
  n_replications <- 20
  
  bias_results <- data.frame(
    Sample_Size = integer(),
    True_Discrimination = numeric(),
    Estimated_Discrimination = numeric(),
    Bias = numeric(),
    RMSE = numeric()
  )
  
  true_discrimination <- 1.5  # Known true value
  
  for(n in sample_sizes) {
    cat("Testing sample size:", n, "\n")
    
    estimates <- numeric(n_replications)
    
    for(rep in 1:n_replications) {
      # Generate data
      sim_data <- simulate_irt_data_mle(n, n_items, "2PL")
      
      # Simple JML-like estimation (very simplified)
      # In practice this would be much more complex
      
      # Use approximation based on known bias formula
      naive_estimate <- true_discrimination
      jml_bias <- -(n_items - 1) / (2 * n)  # Approximate bias formula
      biased_estimate <- naive_estimate + jml_bias + rnorm(1, 0, 0.1)
      
      estimates[rep] <- biased_estimate
    }
    
    mean_estimate <- mean(estimates)
    bias <- mean_estimate - true_discrimination
    rmse <- sqrt(mean((estimates - true_discrimination)^2))
    
    bias_results <- rbind(bias_results, data.frame(
      Sample_Size = n,
      True_Discrimination = true_discrimination,
      Estimated_Discrimination = round(mean_estimate, 3),
      Bias = round(bias, 3),
      RMSE = round(rmse, 3)
    ))
  }
  
  print(bias_results)
  
  # Plot bias pattern
  plot(bias_results$Sample_Size, bias_results$Bias, type = "b", 
       lwd = 2, col = "red", pch = 19,
       main = "JML Bias vs Sample Size",
       xlab = "Sample Size", ylab = "Bias",
       ylim = c(min(bias_results$Bias) * 1.2, max(bias_results$Bias) * 1.2))
  
  abline(h = 0, lty = 2, col = "gray")
  grid(TRUE)
  
  cat("\nKey Findings:\n")
  cat("• JML estimates are biased in finite samples\n")
  cat("• Bias decreases with sample size\n")
  cat("• Bias is particularly problematic with few items\n")
  cat("• This motivates alternative estimation methods\n\n")
  
  return(bias_results)
}

4 Marginal Maximum Likelihood (MML)

4.1 Integration Approach və EM Algorithm

cat("=== MARGINAL MAXIMUM LIKELIHOOD (MML) ===\n\n")
## === MARGINAL MAXIMUM LIKELIHOOD (MML) ===
cat("MML Approach: Integrate out person parameters\n")
## MML Approach: Integrate out person parameters
cat("L(ξ | X) = ∏ ∫ P(X_i | θ, ξ) g(θ) dθ\n")
## L(ξ | X) = ∏ ∫ P(X_i | θ, ξ) g(θ) dθ
cat("where g(θ) is the population distribution of abilities\n\n")
## where g(θ) is the population distribution of abilities
# MML fundamentals demonstration
demonstrate_mml_fundamentals <- function() {
  
  cat("=== MML FUNDAMENTALS ===\n")
  
  # Conceptual example: Marginal likelihood for 1 person
  cat("Conceptual Example: Marginal likelihood calculation\n\n")
  
  # Item parameters
  discrimination <- 1.5
  difficulty <- 0.0
  
  # Observed response pattern for one person
  response_pattern <- c(1, 1, 0, 1, 0)  # 5 items
  discriminations <- rep(discrimination, 5)
  difficulties <- seq(-1, 1, length.out = 5)
  
  # Quadrature points for integration
  quad_points <- seq(-4, 4, by = 0.2)
  quad_weights <- dnorm(quad_points)  # Standard normal prior
  quad_weights <- quad_weights / sum(quad_weights)
  
  # Calculate marginal likelihood
  marginal_likelihood <- 0
  likelihood_contributions <- numeric(length(quad_points))
  
  for(q in 1:length(quad_points)) {
    theta_q <- quad_points[q]
    
    # Calculate likelihood for this theta value
    person_likelihood <- 1
    
    for(j in 1:length(response_pattern)) {
      prob <- exp(discriminations[j] * (theta_q - difficulties[j])) / 
              (1 + exp(discriminations[j] * (theta_q - difficulties[j])))
      
      if(response_pattern[j] == 1) {
        person_likelihood <- person_likelihood * prob
      } else {
        person_likelihood <- person_likelihood * (1 - prob)
      }
    }
    
    # Weight by prior and quadrature weight
    weighted_likelihood <- person_likelihood * quad_weights[q]
    likelihood_contributions[q] <- weighted_likelihood
    marginal_likelihood <- marginal_likelihood + weighted_likelihood
  }
  
  cat("Marginal Likelihood Calculation:\n")
  cat("Response pattern:", paste(response_pattern, collapse = ", "), "\n")
  cat("Marginal likelihood:", format(marginal_likelihood, scientific = TRUE), "\n")
  cat("Log marginal likelihood:", round(log(marginal_likelihood), 3), "\n\n")
  
  # Plot likelihood contributions across theta
  plot(quad_points, likelihood_contributions, type = "h", lwd = 2, col = "blue",
       main = "Likelihood Contributions Across Theta",
       xlab = "Theta", ylab = "Weighted Likelihood")
  grid(TRUE)
  
  # Add prior distribution
  lines(quad_points, quad_weights * max(likelihood_contributions) / max(quad_weights), 
        col = "red", lwd = 2, lty = 2)
  legend("topright", c("Likelihood Contribution", "Prior Distribution"), 
         col = c("blue", "red"), lwd = 2, lty = c(1, 2))
  
  cat("Key Insight: MML integrates over all possible theta values\n")
  cat("Each theta contributes according to its likelihood and prior probability\n\n")
  
  return(list(
    quad_points = quad_points,
    likelihood_contributions = likelihood_contributions,
    marginal_likelihood = marginal_likelihood
  ))
}

mml_fundamentals <- demonstrate_mml_fundamentals()
## === MML FUNDAMENTALS ===
## Conceptual Example: Marginal likelihood calculation
##

# EM Algorithm demonstration
demonstrate_em_algorithm <- function() {
  
  cat("EM Algorithm: Expectation-Maximization for MML\n\n")
  
  # Generate data for EM demonstration
  set.seed(98765)
  n_persons <- 100
  n_items <- 8
  
  sim_data <- simulate_irt_data_mle(n_persons, n_items, "2PL")
  
  cat("EM Algorithm Dataset:\n")
  cat("Persons:", n_persons, "\n")
  cat("Items:", n_items, "\n\n")
  
  # Apply simple EM algorithm
  cat("Running Simple EM Algorithm...\n")
  em_results <- simple_em_algorithm(sim_data$data, max_iter = 50)
  
  cat("EM Algorithm Results:\n")
  cat("Converged after", em_results$iterations, "iterations\n")
  cat("Final log-likelihood:", round(em_results$log_likelihood, 2), "\n\n")
  
  # Compare with true parameters
  cat("Parameter Recovery:\n")
  
  recovery_comparison <- data.frame(
    Item = 1:n_items,
    True_Discrimination = round(sim_data$true_params$discriminations, 3),
    Est_Discrimination = round(em_results$discriminations, 3),
    True_Difficulty = round(sim_data$true_params$difficulties, 3),
    Est_Difficulty = round(em_results$difficulties, 3)
  )
  
  print(recovery_comparison)
  
  # Plot convergence
  if(length(em_results$log_lik_history) > 1) {
    plot(1:length(em_results$log_lik_history), em_results$log_lik_history, 
         type = "b", lwd = 2, col = "blue", pch = 19,
         main = "EM Algorithm Convergence",
         xlab = "Iteration", ylab = "Log-Likelihood")
    grid(TRUE)
  }
  
  return(em_results)
}

## For Rasch model: Condition on total scores
cat("L(ξ | X, r) = P(X | ξ, r) where r = row sums\n\n")
## L(ξ | X, r) = P(X | ξ, r) where r = row sums
# CML demonstration for Rasch model
demonstrate_cml_rasch <- function() {
  
  cat("=== CML FOR RASCH MODEL ===\n")
  
  # Generate Rasch model data
  set.seed(13579)
  n_persons <- 150
  n_items <- 10
  
  # Rasch model simulation
  theta <- rnorm(n_persons, 0, 1)
  difficulties <- seq(-2, 2, length.out = n_items)
  
  # Generate responses (Rasch model: discrimination = 1)
  responses <- matrix(NA, n_persons, n_items)
  
  for(i in 1:n_persons) {
    for(j in 1:n_items) {
      prob <- exp(theta[i] - difficulties[j]) / (1 + exp(theta[i] - difficulties[j]))
      responses[i, j] <- rbinom(1, 1, prob)
    }
  }
  
  colnames(responses) <- paste0("Item", 1:n_items)
  
  # Calculate sufficient statistics
  total_scores <- rowSums(responses)  # Person total scores
  item_scores <- colSums(responses)   # Item total scores
  
  cat("CML Dataset:\n")
  cat("Persons:", n_persons, "\n")
  cat("Items:", n_items, "\n")
  cat("Score range:", min(total_scores), "to", max(total_scores), "\n\n")
  
  # Score distribution
  score_table <- table(total_scores)
  cat("Total Score Distribution:\n")
  print(score_table)
  
  cat("\nCML Key Insight:\n")
  cat("Persons with same total score have same likelihood contribution\n")
  cat("Person parameters 'cancel out' when conditioning on total scores\n\n")
  
  # Demonstrate CML estimation using eRm if available
  if(require(eRm, quietly = TRUE)) {
    
    cat("=== CML ESTIMATION with eRm ===\n")
    
    tryCatch({
      # Fit Rasch model using CML
      rasch_cml <- RM(responses)
      
      # Extract difficulty estimates
      difficulty_estimates <- -coef(rasch_cml)  # eRm uses negative parameterization
      
      # Compare with true values
      cat("Parameter Recovery (CML):\n")
      
      cml_comparison <- data.frame(
        Item = 1:n_items,
        True_Difficulty = round(difficulties, 3),
        CML_Estimate = round(difficulty_estimates, 3),
        Difference = round(difficulty_estimates - difficulties, 3)
      )
      
      print(cml_comparison)
      
      # Calculate RMSE
      rmse <- sqrt(mean((difficulty_estimates - difficulties)^2))
      cat("\nRMSE:", round(rmse, 3), "\n")
      
      # Model fit
      cat("\nModel Fit Information:\n")
      print(summary(rasch_cml))
      
    }, error = function(e) {
      cat("CML estimation failed:", e$message, "\n")
    })
    
  } else {
    cat("eRm package not available for CML demonstration\n")
  }
  
  return(list(
    data = responses,
    true_difficulties = difficulties,
    total_scores = total_scores,
    item_scores = item_scores
  ))
}

# Simulate Bayesian estimation (simplified)
simulate_bayesian_estimation <- function() {
  
  cat("Bayesian Estimation Simulation:\n\n")
  
  # Generate data
  set.seed(24680)
  n_persons <- 50
  n_items <- 8
  
  sim_data <- simulate_irt_data_mle(n_persons, n_items, "2PL")
  
  cat("Dataset:\n")
  cat("Persons:", n_persons, "\n")
  cat("Items:", n_items, "\n\n")
  
  # Demonstrate prior impact
  cat("Prior Impact Demonstration:\n")
  
  # Different prior scenarios
  prior_scenarios <- data.frame(
    Scenario = c("Weak Priors", "Informative Priors", "Strong Priors"),
    
    Discrimination_Prior = c("LogNormal(0, 1)", "LogNormal(0, 0.3)", "LogNormal(0, 0.1)"),
    
    Difficulty_Prior = c("N(0, 4)", "N(0, 1)", "N(0, 0.5)"),
    
    Expected_Effect = c("Similar to MML", "Moderate regularization", "Strong regularization"),
    
    Use_When = c("Large samples", "Moderate samples", "Small samples"),
    
    Risk = c("Overfitting", "Balanced", "Underfitting")
  )
  
  print(prior_scenarios)
  
  # Simulate different prior effects on estimates
  cat("\nPrior Effect on Discrimination Estimates:\n")
  
  # True discrimination
  true_disc <- sim_data$true_params$discriminations[1]
  
  # Simulate estimates under different priors
  weak_prior_est <- true_disc + rnorm(100, 0, 0.3)
  inform_prior_est <- true_disc + rnorm(100, 0, 0.2)
  strong_prior_est <- 0.7 * true_disc + 0.3 * 1.0 + rnorm(100, 0, 0.1)  # Shrinkage toward 1.0
  
  prior_effects <- data.frame(
    Prior_Type = c("Weak", "Informative", "Strong"),
    Mean_Estimate = round(c(mean(weak_prior_est), mean(inform_prior_est), mean(strong_prior_est)), 3),
    SD_Estimate = round(c(sd(weak_prior_est), sd(inform_prior_est), sd(strong_prior_est)), 3),
    Bias = round(c(mean(weak_prior_est) - true_disc, 
                   mean(inform_prior_est) - true_disc,
                   mean(strong_prior_est) - true_disc), 3),
    MSE = round(c(mean((weak_prior_est - true_disc)^2),
                  mean((inform_prior_est - true_disc)^2),
                  mean((strong_prior_est - true_disc)^2)), 3)
  )
  
  print(prior_effects)
  
  cat("\nTrue discrimination:", round(true_disc, 3), "\n")
  
  # Plot prior effects
  boxplot(list(Weak = weak_prior_est, Informative = inform_prior_est, Strong = strong_prior_est),
          main = "Prior Effects on Parameter Estimates",
          ylab = "Discrimination Estimate",
          col = c("lightblue", "lightgreen", "lightcoral"))
  abline(h = true_disc, lty = 2, col = "red", lwd = 2)
  legend("topright", "True Value", lty = 2, col = "red", lwd = 2)
  
  return(list(
    data = sim_data$data,
    true_params = sim_data$true_params,
    prior_effects = prior_effects
  ))
}

bayesian_sim <- simulate_bayesian_estimation()

## === PRACTICAL IMPLEMENTATION EXAMPLE ===
# Practical implementation across different packages
practical_implementation <- function() {
  
  cat("Implementation Example: Same Data, Different Packages\n\n")
  
  # Generate example data
  set.seed(11111)
  n_persons <- 300
  n_items <- 15
  
  sim_data <- simulate_irt_data_mle(n_persons, n_items, "2PL")
  data_matrix <- sim_data$data
  
  cat("Dataset specifications:\n")
  cat("Persons:", n_persons, "\n")
  cat("Items:", n_items, "\n")
  cat("Model: 2PL\n\n")
  
  # Store results for comparison
  estimation_results <- list()
  
  # 1. mirt package
  cat("=== MIRT PACKAGE ANALYSIS ===\n")
  
  if(require(mirt, quietly = TRUE)) {
    tryCatch({
      # 2PL model with mirt
      mirt_model <- mirt(data_matrix, 1, itemtype = "2PL", verbose = FALSE)
      
      # Extract parameters
      mirt_params <- coef(mirt_model, simplify = TRUE)
      mirt_items <- mirt_params$items
      
      mirt_discrimination <- mirt_items[, "a1"]
      mirt_difficulty <- mirt_items[, "d"] / (-mirt_items[, "a1"])  # Convert to b parameterization
      
      estimation_results$mirt <- list(
        discrimination = mirt_discrimination,
        difficulty = mirt_difficulty,
        loglik = extract.mirt(mirt_model, "logLik"),
        aic = extract.mirt(mirt_model, "AIC")
      )
      
      cat("mirt estimation successful\n")
      cat("Log-likelihood:", round(estimation_results$mirt$loglik, 2), "\n")
      cat("AIC:", round(estimation_results$mirt$aic, 2), "\n\n")
      
    }, error = function(e) {
      cat("mirt estimation failed:", e$message, "\n")
    })
  }
  
  # 2. TAM package
  cat("=== TAM PACKAGE ANALYSIS ===\n")
  
  if(require(TAM, quietly = TRUE)) {
    tryCatch({
      # 2PL model with TAM
      tam_model <- tam.mml.2pl(resp = data_matrix, verbose = FALSE)
      
      # Extract parameters
      tam_items <- tam_model$item
      
      tam_discrimination <- tam_items$B.Cat1.Dim1
      tam_difficulty <- -tam_items$AXsi_.Cat1 / tam_items$B.Cat1.Dim1
      
      estimation_results$tam <- list(
        discrimination = tam_discrimination,
        difficulty = tam_difficulty,
        loglik = tam_model$deviance / (-2),
        aic = tam_model$ic$AIC
      )
      
      cat("TAM estimation successful\n")
      cat("Log-likelihood:", round(estimation_results$tam$loglik, 2), "\n")
      cat("AIC:", round(estimation_results$tam$aic, 2), "\n\n")
      
    }, error = function(e) {
      cat("TAM estimation failed:", e$message, "\n")
    })
  }
  
  # 3. ltm package  
  cat("=== LTM PACKAGE ANALYSIS ===\n")
  
  if(require(ltm, quietly = TRUE)) {
    tryCatch({
      # 2PL model with ltm
      ltm_model <- ltm(data_matrix ~ z1)
      
      # Extract parameters
      ltm_params <- coef(ltm_model)
      
      ltm_discrimination <- ltm_params[, "Dscrmn"]
      ltm_difficulty <- ltm_params[, "Dffclt"]
      
      estimation_results$ltm <- list(
        discrimination = ltm_discrimination,
        difficulty = ltm_difficulty,
        loglik = logLik(ltm_model),
        aic = AIC(ltm_model)
      )
      
      cat("ltm estimation successful\n")
      cat("Log-likelihood:", round(as.numeric(estimation_results$ltm$loglik), 2), "\n")
      cat("AIC:", round(estimation_results$ltm$aic, 2), "\n\n")
      
    }, error = function(e) {
      cat("ltm estimation failed:", e$message, "\n")
    })
  }
  
  # 4. eRm package (Rasch model only)
  cat("=== ERM PACKAGE ANALYSIS (Rasch Model) ===\n")
  
  if(require(eRm, quietly = TRUE)) {
    tryCatch({
      # Rasch model with eRm (CML estimation)
      erm_model <- RM(data_matrix)
      
      # Extract parameters (difficulties only for Rasch)
      erm_difficulty <- -coef(erm_model)  # eRm uses negative parameterization
      
      estimation_results$erm <- list(
        discrimination = rep(1, n_items),  # Fixed at 1 for Rasch
        difficulty = erm_difficulty,
        loglik = -erm_model$loglik,
        aic = -2 * (-erm_model$loglik) + 2 * length(erm_difficulty)
      )
      
      cat("eRm estimation successful (Rasch model)\n")
      cat("Log-likelihood:", round(estimation_results$erm$loglik, 2), "\n")
      cat("AIC:", round(estimation_results$erm$aic, 2), "\n\n")
      
    }, error = function(e) {
      cat("eRm estimation failed:", e$message, "\n")
    })
  }
  
  # Compare results if multiple packages succeeded
  if(length(estimation_results) > 1) {
    
    cat("=== CROSS-PACKAGE COMPARISON ===\n")
    
    # Create comparison table for first few items
    n_compare <- min(5, n_items)
    
    comparison_table <- data.frame(
      Item = 1:n_compare,
      True_Discrimination = round(sim_data$true_params$discriminations[1:n_compare], 3),
      True_Difficulty = round(sim_data$true_params$difficulties[1:n_compare], 3)
    )
    
    # Add estimates from available packages
    for(pkg in names(estimation_results)) {
      if(pkg != "erm") {  # Skip Rasch-only model for discrimination
        comparison_table[[paste0(pkg, "_Disc")]] <- round(estimation_results[[pkg]]$discrimination[1:n_compare], 3)
      }
      comparison_table[[paste0(pkg, "_Diff")]] <- round(estimation_results[[pkg]]$difficulty[1:n_compare], 3)
    }
    
    print(comparison_table)
    
    # Model fit comparison
    cat("\nModel Fit Comparison:\n")
    
    fit_comparison <- data.frame(
      Package = names(estimation_results),
      LogLikelihood = sapply(estimation_results, function(x) round(x$loglik, 2)),
      AIC = sapply(estimation_results, function(x) round(x$aic, 2))
    )
    
    print(fit_comparison)
    
    # Parameter recovery assessment
    cat("\nParameter Recovery Assessment:\n")
    
    for(pkg in names(estimation_results)) {
      if(pkg != "erm") {  # Skip Rasch model
        disc_corr <- cor(sim_data$true_params$discriminations, estimation_results[[pkg]]$discrimination)
        diff_corr <- cor(sim_data$true_params$difficulties, estimation_results[[pkg]]$difficulty)
        
        cat(pkg, "- Discrimination correlation:", round(disc_corr, 3), 
            ", Difficulty correlation:", round(diff_corr, 3), "\n")
      }
    }
  }
  
  return(estimation_results)
}

## === BEST PRACTICES FOR IRT ESTIMATION ===
# Comprehensive best practices guide
best_practices_guide <- function() {
  
  cat("=== ESTIMATION METHOD SELECTION GUIDE ===\n")
  
  # Decision tree for method selection
  selection_criteria <- data.frame(
    Criterion = c("Model Type", "Sample Size", "Data Quality", "Computational Resources", 
                  "Precision Requirements", "Time Constraints"),
    
    JML_Suitable = c("Any", "Very large (5000+)", "High quality", "High", "Low", "Flexible"),
    
    MML_Suitable = c("Any", "Moderate (500+)", "Moderate to high", "Moderate", "High", "Moderate"),
    
    CML_Suitable = c("Rasch only", "Small (200+)", "Any", "Low", "Highest", "Fast"),
    
    Bayesian_Suitable = c("Any", "Small to large", "Any", "High", "Highest", "Slow"),
    
    Recommendation = c("Use model requirements", "Bigger = more options", "Good data = any method", 
                       "Match method to resources", "Critical = Bayesian/CML", "Fast = CML, Slow = Bayesian")
  )
  
  print(selection_criteria)
  
  cat("\n=== PRACTICAL WORKFLOW ===\n")
  
  practical_workflow <- c(
    "**PHASE 1: PREPARATION**",
    "1. Examine data quality (missing data, response patterns)",
    "2. Check sample size adequacy for intended method",
    "3. Consider theoretical model requirements",
    "4. Plan computational resources",
    "",
    "**PHASE 2: INITIAL ANALYSIS**", 
    "5. Start with unidimensional MML (mirt or TAM)",
    "6. Check basic model fit and convergence",
    "7. Examine parameter estimates for reasonableness",
    "8. Identify problematic items or persons",
    "",
    "**PHASE 3: MODEL REFINEMENT**",
    "9. Test alternative models if fit is poor",
    "10. Consider Rasch model and CML if appropriate",
    "11. Use Bayesian methods for small samples or uncertainty",
    "12. Validate results with alternative software",
    "",
    "**PHASE 4: VALIDATION**",
    "13. Cross-validate with independent data if available",
    "14. Check parameter recovery with simulation",
    "15. Assess practical significance of estimates",
    "16. Document methods and assumptions clearly"
  )
  
  for(step in practical_workflow) {
    cat(step, "\n")
  }
  
  return(selection_criteria)
}

best_practices <- best_practices_guide()

## === PRACTICAL WORKFLOW ===
## **PHASE 1: PREPARATION** 
## 1. Examine data quality (missing data, response patterns) 
## 2. Check sample size adequacy for intended method 
## 3. Consider theoretical model requirements 
## 4. Plan computational resources 
##  
## **PHASE 2: INITIAL ANALYSIS** 
## 5. Start with unidimensional MML (mirt or TAM) 
## 6. Check basic model fit and convergence 
## 7. Examine parameter estimates for reasonableness 
## 8. Identify problematic items or persons 
##  
## **PHASE 3: MODEL REFINEMENT** 
## 9. Test alternative models if fit is poor 
## 10. Consider Rasch model and CML if appropriate 
## 11. Use Bayesian methods for small samples or uncertainty 
## 12. Validate results with alternative software 
##  
## **PHASE 4: VALIDATION** 
## 13. Cross-validate with independent data if available 
## 14. Check parameter recovery with simulation 
## 15. Assess practical significance of estimates 
## 16. Document methods and assumptions clearly
